m_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) registered voters from November 14-18, just a=
s news cycles were popping off with Trump=E2=80=99s cabinet announcements, =
and found that 53 percent of voters approve of the way Trump is handling th=
e transition. Only 40 percent of voters disapproved.

That=E2=80=99s to be expected after an election, when voters usually welcom=
e an incoming president with some goodwill. But with Trump, there=E2=80=99s=
 a political paradox at work: While Trump himself remains personally unpopu=
lar, voters still want him to succeed. A sizable majority of voters (58 per=
cent) say it=E2=80=99s likely =E2=80=9Cthe country
will start to head in a better direction in 2025,=E2=80=9D while only 38 pe=
rcent said the opposite. The percentage of Americans who say the country is=
 on the right track is still low (30 percent), but it=E2=80=99s up by a few=
 points compared to Echelon=E2=80=99s final pre-election poll in October.

As for Trump=E2=80=99s cabinet picks, some are more popular than others, an=
d most of them aren=E2=80=99t well known to the American public. Among the =
names in the news lately, Kennedy has the best favorability ratings, with 4=
